deck: "Blood Money: The Road To Detroit" is a graphic novel published by Ashur Collective on October 17th, 2013.
description:
"Blood Money: The Road To Detroit" is a graphic novel published by Ashur Collective on October 17th, 2013. Originally a novel manuscript, its creators, J. Acocella and K. Guillory, decided to illustrate it as a comic first in order to garner interest for a possible series.

The graphic novel originally generated seed capital via an Indiegogo campaign, and was pitched in July 2013 as a business idea to Wayne State University in Detroit, Michigan and its business incubator, Blackstone LaunchPad, as a part of their Warrior Fund business grant program. Being the first and only artistic venture to apply, Ashur Collective successfully secured seed capital for production, printing, and promotion costs, doing so in a business program previously seeing applications only from tech and medical ventures.

Their premiere party was held on October 17th, 2013 at the Untitled Bottega gallery in Detroit, Michigan, accompanied by clothing label Creep Street. From there, the book was promoted at Youmacon and Detroit Fanfare.

In November 2013, Ashur Collective announced editing had begun in order to produce the novel counterpart. A sequel is also planned for future release, along with several related manuscripts for graphic novels that are already written.

Production

K. Guillory has stated that in illustrating the book, they took special care to reference real locations. The goal was to produce a book Detroiters would feel told an "authentic" story, as well as giving those not from Detroit a better understanding of different parts of the city. Along with this, are special themes mentioned:

  • "Tourism" areas receiving more police attention than areas with considerably less cash flow
  • Social commentary through graffiti
  • Detroit's bankruptcy and emergency management
  • The delay of projects to improve the city, such as the proposed light rail system
  • Objectification of both genders from the opposite sex, and "female chauvinist pigs"
  • Detroit City Council decisions delayed through lawsuits, as a typical measure to stop propositions from moving forward
  • The arrest of Kwame Kilpatrick
  • The effect of marijuana legalization

Sequel

"Blood Money: The Spellbook Version" will see publication in February 2014. Afterwards, the next book in the series, "The Other World", will begin production as a graphic novel.
name: Blood Money: The Road To Detroit

Not known if there was an issue number 1. Date of issue uncertain.

Read more about Hadacol on Wikipedia: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hadacol ,

description:
English translation of the Japanese manga Uchi no Shachou wa Cherry desu. (うちの社長はチェリーです。).

Tomoe is a respectable president of his designing company, but from sheer (and strange) coincidence, at Tomoe's 33rd birthday party, all his co-workers find out that he is actually still a virgin. Everybody is shocked at this fact since Tomoe seems to be the perfect man whom anybody would want to be with! After hearing about Tomoe's surprising virginity, Koshimaru - a man who is both Tomoe's best friend from college and business partner - begins to feel a certain attraction toward Tomoe. Is this the slightly awkward beginning to an intimate relationship?
name: Deflower the Boss
